  "prompt": "Can the statement \"X is n times less or smaller than Y be justified when n>1?",
  "response": "The phrasing \"X is _n_ times less than Y\" or \"X is _n_ times smaller than Y\" is **ambiguous and often considered incorrect**, especially when _n_\u202f>\u202f1. Here's why:\n\n### Mathematical Interpretation Issues\n\n1. **Literal Interpretation:**\n   - \"X is _n_ times less than Y\" might be interpreted as:\n     \\[\n     X = Y - n \\times Y = Y \\times (1 - n)\n     \\]\n     For _n_\u202f>\u202f1, this would imply that X is a negative value, which is likely not the intended meaning.\n\n2. **Common Misunderstanding:**\n   - Many people use \"n times less\" to mean \"X is \\( \\frac{1}{n} \\) of Y\" (i.e., \\( X = \\frac{Y}{n} \\)), but this is **not** a mathematically precise way to express the relationship and can lead to confusion.\n\n### Preferred Alternatives\n\nTo convey the intended meaning clearly and accurately, consider using one of the following alternatives:\n\n- **\"X is \\( \\frac{1}{n} \\) of Y\":**\n  \\[\n  X = \\frac{Y}{n}\n  \\]\n  This is mathematically precise and leaves no room for misinterpretation.\n\n- **\"Y is _n_ times larger than X\":**\n  \\[\n  Y = n \\times X\n  \\]\n  This phrasing clearly indicates the multiplicative relationship without ambiguity.\n\n- **\"X is decreased by a factor of _n_ compared to Y\":**\n  This communicates that X is smaller by a specific multiplicative factor.\n\n### Language Considerations\n\nEven outside of strict mathematical contexts, the phrases \"times less\" or \"times smaller\" can be confusing or misinterpreted by readers or listeners. Clear and unambiguous language fosters better understanding, especially in technical or academic settings.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nWhile you might encounter the phrases \"n times less\" or \"n times smaller\" in informal contexts, **they are not recommended for precise communication**, particularly when _n_\u202f>\u202f1. Opt for clearer alternatives to convey the intended meaning accurately.",
